exports[`M0 golden — blocked-conclusion fixture essay snapshot — blocked conclusion (deliberative / informed) 1`] = `
"# Blocked Conclusion: AI moratorium claim

*A simple chain whose conclusion is blocked by an unanswered objection in the deliberation's refusal surface.*

---

The question before us is whether a 6-month moratorium on frontier-model training is warranted, given an unanswered relocation-of-risk objection. This essay traces a sequence of interconnected arguments, each building upon its predecessor in a logical chain.

The analysis begins from two foundational considerations: "Frontier-model benchmark scores have doubled year-over-year."; and "A unilateral moratorium would shift frontier development to less safety-consciou...".

Frontier-model benchmark scores have doubled year-over-year.

Against this view, a unilateral moratorium would shift frontier development to less safety-conscious actors.

By contrast, the opposing view counters that the same validity claim — Unanswered relocation-of-risk objection.

It remains an open question whether a 6-month moratorium on frontier-model training is warranted. Plausibly, on the available evidence, this follows from the fact that Capability gains are outpacing alignment research.


---

The recognition that the same thesis supplies one strand toward the still-open question of whether a 6-month moratorium on frontier-model training is warranted, though the chain's conclusion remains blocked.

---

Taking stock, two premises survive the foregoing exchange: Frontier-model benchmark scores have doubled year-over-year; and a unilateral moratorium would shift frontier development to less safety-conscious actors.

A residual contested band persists, leaving open whether this same position stands? These questions remain live and the conclusions above should be read against them.

This chain's conclusion remains blocked by one unanswered objection; the weakest link is the unanswered relocation-of-risk objection. Do not read the above as a closed verdict.

These standings are provisional: the arguments give reasons for belief, not proof beyond doubt."
